<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/world <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/world" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 8 月 15 日，星期二 22:23:21 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[U.S. in Talks to Develop Ukraine’s Grain Export Routes]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>俄罗斯退出安全协议后，与土耳其、基辅和其他国家的讨论重点是未来收成的替代渠道<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001136525"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835934?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">罗马尼亚康斯坦察黑海港的一个粮食码头是乌克兰出口的中转站。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：daniel mihailescu/法新社/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001136525"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jared-malsin" itemprop="url" rel="author">贾里德·马尔辛</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/laurence-norman" itemprop="url" rel="author">劳伦斯·诺曼</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 15 日下午 1:15 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-in-talks-to-develop-ukraine-grain-export-routes-3e597c3"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>伊斯坦布尔——官员们表示，在俄罗斯退出<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/great-power-rivalry-looms-over-ukraine-grain-deal-3d2e0eb1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">保证黑海食品运输安全的</a>协议后，美国正在与土耳其、乌克兰和基辅邻国进行谈判，以增加乌克兰谷物替代出口路线的使用。</p><p>美国支持的计划包括增加乌克兰在 10 月份之前每月通过多瑙河出口 400 万吨谷物的能力。大部分谷物将顺河而下，经黑海运往罗马尼亚附近的港口，然后运往其他目的地。尽管速度较慢且成本较高，但这条航线将作为去年根据与俄罗斯、土耳其和联合国达成的协议建立的黑海航运走廊的替代方案。</p><p>俄罗斯于 7 月<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-russia-killed-the-ukraine-grain-deal-faf1f8c5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">退出该协议</a>，导致乌克兰从敖德萨周围三个港口的出口停止，并导致黑海冲突升级。最近几周，俄罗斯军队对乌克兰港口<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-strikes-odesa-port-after-quitting-black-sea-grain-deal-4df967bd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">发动了一波导弹和无人机袭击</a>，并于周日登上了一艘前往乌克兰的商船。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="736" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/313c2c2b-ee53-4b10-925e-6cac55c527ff-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>西方对黑海粮食计划替代方案的规划表明，美国、乌克兰和欧洲国家正在为俄罗斯未能及时重新加入该协议以转移乌克兰夏季和秋季收成的情况做准备。</p><p>一位驻华盛顿的美国高级官员表示：“现实情况是，俄罗斯已决定攻击全球粮食供应，在它认为攻击结束之前，很难将其挽回。”</p><p>由于乌克兰是小麦、玉米和葵花籽油的最大出口国，因此粮食协议被认为对于保持全球低食品价格至关重要。据美国国务院称，自俄罗斯上个月退出黑海协议以来，食品价格已上涨 10%。联合国称，俄罗斯入侵乌克兰是近年来导致世界各地数百万人濒临饥饿的一系列危机之一</p><p>官员们表示，在努力增加乌克兰通过多瑙河的出口能力的同时，土耳其和联合国也在努力说服俄罗斯重新加入粮食协议。外交官称，去年帮助促成该协议的土耳其总统雷杰普·塔伊普·埃尔多安面临着在乌克兰收获的谷物于 9 月初开始堆积之前恢复该协议的压力。</p><p>这位华盛顿官员表示，美国正在考虑所有可能的选择，包括军事解决方案，以保护进出乌克兰多瑙河港口的船只，但拒绝透露这些选择的具体细节，也拒绝透露哪些国家将参与其中。</p><p> “我们将考虑一切，”这位官员在谈到保护航道的努力时说道。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="470" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835927?width=700&amp;height=470" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 7月底，运粮卡车等待进入罗马尼亚康斯坦察港口。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：daniel mihailescu/法新社/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>美国国务院表示，美国高级官员周五在罗马尼亚加拉茨市举行的一次会议上与乌克兰、摩尔多瓦和北大西洋公约组织成员国罗马尼亚领导人讨论了这一努力。罗马尼亚交通部长随后告诉记者，该国粮食出口能力将增加一倍，达到每月 400 万吨。</p><p>土耳其外交部没有回应就本周与美国会谈发表评论的请求</p><p>美国的计划将部分借鉴欧盟的一项倡议，即建立<a href="https://eu-solidarity-ukraine.ec.europa.eu/eu-assistance-ukraine/eu-ukraine-solidarity-lanes_en" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">被称为“团结通道”的</a>公路、铁路和海上航线，以尽可能顺利地将谷物和其他货物运进和运出乌克兰。</p><p>欧盟在战争爆发的头几个月制定了该计划，此前签署了道路运输协议，为运输商在乌克兰、摩尔多瓦和欧盟之间无需许可证的情况下过境铺平了道路。此后，欧盟投资了一系列基础设施项目，以建立更快的出口通道并加快海关程序。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1690" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/670c660e-e0c9-43e9-8c6d-a5cb03e5d9e4-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>自2022年5月以来，这些航线已允许乌克兰出口4100万吨粮食，大大超过黑海粮食倡议所实现的目标。欧盟农业专员</p>贾努什·沃伊切霍夫斯基上个月表示，几个月内，欧盟的团结航线可能会取代乌克兰所有黑海谷物航线。<p></p><p>欧盟官员私下表示，他们相信，如果一切顺利的话，欧盟可以允许乌克兰平均每月出口500万至550万吨粮食。迄今为止，欧盟通道的最大成绩是11月份乌克兰谷物出口量为420万吨。 6月份，乌克兰通过欧盟倡议仅出口了300万吨。欧盟官员表示，多瑙河航线占据了大部分出口，约占 60%。去年，黑海谷物倡议在鼎盛时期使乌克兰每月可以从敖德萨周围的三个港口出口约 600 万吨粮食。</p><p>然而，团结之路也遇到了困难。</p><p>欧盟官员表示，一些路线没有足够的人员和资源来迅速对入境货物进行必要的卫生和海关检查，有时会导致积压和延误，从而减缓交通并推高公路运输价格，从而推高乌克兰谷物的价格出口。乌克兰和罗马尼亚之间曾因乌克兰疏浚多瑙河三角洲运河以使运粮船只顺利通行而产生争议，现已解决。</p><p>美国官员表示，他们正在讨论提高多瑙河航线的效率，以允许更大的船只通过，为停泊空间腾出空间，并增加可用于通过重要运河运送船只的引航员数量。</p><p>然而，这些努力“不会取代黑海港口，首先是敖德萨，因此这不是解决方案；这确实是一个临时替代方案，”美国国际开发署欧洲和欧亚局助理局长艾琳·伊丽莎白·麦基（Erin Elizabeth McKee）在本月的一次简报中表示。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835919?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> TQ Samsun 号是黑海粮食倡议下最后一艘离开乌克兰的粮食船，于 7 月经过伊斯坦布尔。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：克里斯·麦格拉思/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>自粮食计划解体以来，多瑙河航线是乌克兰通过黑海出口粮食的唯一剩余途径，较小的船只经常将粮食运往罗马尼亚、保加利亚和其他地方的港口，然后运往世界市场。</p><p>俄罗斯威胁要切断多瑙河航线，本月早些时候袭击了伊兹梅尔河港，并于周日登上了一艘驶向该港口的土耳其船员船只。</p><p>俄罗斯国防部周二发布的一段事件视频显示，武装的俄罗斯士兵将一架直升机降落在该船的甲板上，并审问了船员。乌克兰外交部谴责这次拦截是“挑衅行为”。</p><p>俄罗斯威胁所有前往乌克兰的商船，军事分析人士称，俄罗斯此举是为了封锁进出乌克兰港口的民用船只。</p><p>乌克兰针对俄罗斯的袭击做出了回应， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-sea-drones-alter-balance-of-power-in-black-sea-391cebee?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">使用海上无人机</a>攻击俄罗斯军舰、一艘为莫斯科军队运送喷气燃料的油轮以及一座连接俄罗斯与被占领克里米亚半岛的桥梁。乌克兰还宣布黑海俄罗斯港口周围为“战争风险”地区，这表明俄罗斯自己的航道受到威胁。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="484" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835940?width=700&amp;height=484" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">本月初，俄罗斯无人机袭击摧毁了乌克兰伊兹梅尔河港的一座建筑。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：STRINGER/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>写信给 Jared Malsin <a href="mailto:jared.malsin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">(jared.malsin@wsj.com)</a>和 Laurence Norman ( <a href="mailto:laurence.norman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">laurence.norman@wsj.com</a> )</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 15 Aug 2023 17:15:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-in-talks-to-develop-ukraine-grain-export-routes-3e597c3</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-in-talks-to-develop-ukraine-grain-export-routes-3e597c3<author><![CDATA[Jared MalsinLaurence Norman]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>企业/工业出口</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>市场/营销</category><category>贸易/外部支付</category><category>实物贸易</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>公司的</category><category>工业出口</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>市场</category><category>营销</category><category>贸易</category><category>外部支付</category><category>实物贸易</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[U.K. Arrests Bulgarian Trio Suspected of Spying for Russia]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>此前，西方国家对冒充普通公民的俄罗斯人进行了一系列国际逮捕<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001136221"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835884?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">安全官员警告说，乌克兰战争加剧了俄罗斯间谍活动的威胁。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：彼得·尼科尔斯/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001136221"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/david-luhnow" itemprop="url" rel="author">大卫·卢诺</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/georgi-kantchev" itemprop="url" rel="author">格奥尔基·坎切夫</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 15 日中午 12:38（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-k-arrests-bulgarian-trio-suspected-of-spying-for-russia-1c7455f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>伦敦——英国警方逮捕了五人，其中至少包括三名保加利亚国民，据信他们在为俄罗斯情报部门工作时在英国卧底，这是西方国家一系列逮捕冒充普通人的涉嫌<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/suspected-russian-agent-in-germany-had-access-to-western-intelligence-about-ukraine-war-11672255183?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">俄罗斯特工</a>的最新一起。 。</p><p>英国伦敦警察厅周二表示，三名男子和两名女子因涉嫌违反英国 1911 年《官方保密法》而被捕，该法将间谍活动定为刑事犯罪。大都会称，这五人已获保释，并将于 9 月出庭。</p><p>大都会称，五人中的三人——被大都会认定为 45 岁的奥林·罗塞夫 (Orlin Roussev)、42 岁的比塞尔·赞巴佐夫 (Biser Dzambazov) 和 31 岁的卡特琳·伊万诺娃 (Katrin Ivanova)——也被指控出于不正当目的持有虚假身份证件。</p><p>最先报道这起逮捕事件的英国广播公司 (BBC) 表示，这三人是保加利亚公民，据信为俄罗斯情报部门工作。据称，他们被发现持有来自英国、保加利亚、法国、意大利、西班牙、克罗地亚、斯洛文尼亚、希腊和捷克共和国的伪造护照和文件。</p><p>两名英国政府官员向《华尔街日报》证实了这一报道。</p><p>近几个月来，在多个国家发生了一系列类似的俄罗斯秘密间谍被捕事件， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/brazil-worries-it-has-become-a-haven-for-russian-spies-infiltrating-the-west-525021ba?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">这些间谍通常冒充南美人，</a>但生活在欧洲国家。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=5179E0B0-4C30-4FA3-B4FA-848FF823B8D9&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fu-k-arrests-bulgarian-trio-suspected-of-spying-for-russia-1c7455f&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">英国间谍机构负责人邀请那些对乌克兰战争“默默感到震惊”的俄罗斯人与英国情报部门分享有关克里姆林宫的秘密。照片：马特·邓纳姆/美联社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>一名使用伪造的巴西身份的俄罗斯人在巴西被监禁，并<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-asks-brazil-to-hand-over-russian-accused-of-spying-ddd6a227" target="_blank" class="icon none">在美国面临间谍指控。荷兰</a>当局去年拦截了谢尔盖·切尔卡索夫，因为他据称试图以实习生身份渗透到国际刑事法院。据挪威官员称，另一名被指控的俄罗​​斯间谍在挪威担任大​​学研究员，也使用了假巴西身份。一对冒充阿根廷人的夫妇于四月在斯洛文尼亚被捕，并被指控为俄罗斯从事间谍活动。</p><p>另一对据称是俄罗斯间谍的夫妇——其中一人居住在巴西，另一人居住在希腊——在其他人被捕后不久于四月失踪。</p><p>北欧安全官员警告说，乌克兰战争加剧了俄罗斯间谍活动、 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russian-hackers-step-up-cyber-espionage-against-ukraine-and-allies-microsoft-says-aef4b31e" target="_blank" class="icon none">网络攻击和混合战争</a>的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/norway-to-expel-15-russian-diplomats-accused-of-espionage-aede77e2" target="_blank" class="icon none">威胁</a>。今年三月，波兰<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/poland-says-russian-spies-sought-to-sabotage-western-arms-transfers-to-ukraine-d05361c5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">指控六名外国公民</a>为俄罗斯从事间谍活动、准备破坏活动，以及试图破坏对乌克兰的军事和援助供应。</p><p>此次逮捕行动暴露了俄罗斯在世界各地广泛使用的“非法间谍”网络，除了经常驻扎在其大使馆的官方间谍之外。英国间谍头子、军情五处局长肯·麦卡勒姆去年表示，自乌克兰战争爆发以来，已有 400 多名在大使馆工作的俄罗斯疑似间谍被<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-k-spy-chief-says-russias-spy-network-in-europe-is-dented-following-expulsions-11668606799" target="_blank" class="icon none">驱逐出欧洲</a>，其中包括约 600 名俄罗斯官员。</p><p>就英国而言，三名间谍似乎不是俄罗斯人，而是保加利亚人。罗塞夫住在英格兰东海岸的度假小镇大雅茅斯，赞巴佐夫和伊万诺娃住在伦敦西北部郊区哈罗。</p><p>伦敦查塔姆研究所俄罗斯问题高级顾问研究员凯尔·吉尔斯表示，英国和整个西方国家有俄罗斯间谍或其他国家的人在为俄罗斯从事间谍活动，这并不令人意外。他说，尽管在这种情况下，目前还不清楚保加利亚人正在从事什么类型的情报工作，或者持续了多长时间。</p><p>贾尔斯说：“今天披露的逮捕行动与俄罗斯安插具有南美身份的特工的模式非常不同。”他补充说，保加利亚人可能一直在使用自己的身份。</p><p>罗塞夫的 LinkedIn 页面显示，过去十年他是一家名为 NextGen 的公司的所有者，该公司据称从事人工智能和信号情报业务，拦截私人通信等领域。他还曾在 2008-09 年度担任保加利亚能源部顾问。</p><p>根据他们的社交媒体资料，伊万诺娃和赞巴佐夫经营着“保加利亚社交平台”，这是一个为英国保加利亚人提供帮助的组织。该组织提供文件和其他建议以及免费英语课程方面的帮助。</p><p>伊万诺娃在 2019 年接受保加利亚国家广播电台采访时表示，她和她的伴侣赞巴佐夫于 2012 年搬到伦敦，并开始“从我们的客厅”帮助同胞。五年后，他们开始了社区组织。她说，他们都有全职“夜间工作”，但没有详细说明。她说她有很多“英国朋友”。</p><p>根据她的 LinkedIn 个人资料，伊万诺娃是一名医学实验室助理。根据赞巴佐夫<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/META" class="company-name">Facebook</a>页面上的帖子，他是一名狂热的足球迷。他的最后一篇文章是在 1 月 26 日。</p><p>保加利亚驻英国大使马林·雷科夫 (Marin Raykov) 告诉保加利亚国家通讯社 BTA，大使馆没有关于三名保加利亚人被拘留的任何细节，也没有得到英国当局的通知。雷科夫表示，根据英国惯例，当被拘留的外国人不希望本国得知其被拘留的情况时，英国当局不会通知大使馆。</p><p>近年来，由于俄罗斯特工在英国犯下的罪行，英国与俄罗斯的关系日益紧张。 2018年，俄罗斯特工在索尔兹伯里使用致命神经毒剂企图杀害<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-quiet-english-life-of-sergei-skripal-poisoned-former-russian-spy-1520797449?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">前俄罗斯双重间谍</a>谢尔盖·斯克里帕尔和他的女儿，两人均受重伤。 2006年，另一位前俄罗斯情报官员亚历山大·利特维年科在伦敦被谋杀。</p><p> 7月，英国政府通过了新立法，旨在削弱间谍活动和外国干预的威胁，包括英国选举的威胁。它首次将外国势力未公开的秘密特工定为刑事犯罪。此前的立法仅规定特工向外国势力移交敏感信息为非法行为，但并未将卧底间谍本身定为犯罪。新立法还将破坏英国民主的个人行为定为刑事犯罪，例如干预选举过程、网络攻击或代表外国势力发布虚假信息。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/8d8ed83e-2dd4-4860-bd54-92b7a7ea1ada.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>写信给 David Luhnow <a href="mailto:david.luhnow@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">（david.luhnow@wsj.com）</a>和 Georgi Kantchev（ <a href="mailto:georgi.kantchev@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">georgi.kantchev@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 15 Aug 2023 16:38:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/uk-arrests-bulgarian-trio-suspected-of-spying-for-Russia-1c7455f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/uk-arrests-bulgarian-trio-suspected-of-spying-for-Russia-1c7455f<author><![CDATA[David LuhnowGeorgi Kantchev]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>间谍</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>间谍</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[China Turns to Well-Honed Playbook: Cut Rates, Hide Data]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>停止发布青年失业数据的举措引发了人们对中国经济衰退的不透明性的担忧<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001135735"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="638" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835733?width=860&amp;height=638" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">随着今年夏天最新一​​批毕业生完成学业，经济学家原本预计青年失业率会更高。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Cfoto/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001135735"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jason-douglas" itemprop="url" rel="author">杰森·道格拉斯</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/stella-yifan-xie" itemprop="url" rel="author">斯特拉·谢一凡</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 15 日上午 10:28 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-turns-to-well-honed-playbook-cut-rates-hide-data-bcfdd02"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>中国当局用一套精心设计的策略来应对又一个关于经济<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-slashes-rates-suspends-youth-jobless-data-as-economy-signals-sharper-downturn-418301d6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">的可怕消息</a>：他们降低了利率，并隐瞒了一些可能令人尴尬的经济数据。</p><p>投资者和经济学家表示，问题在于较低的借贷成本和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-locks-information-on-the-country-inside-a-black-box-9c039928?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">更大的不透明度</a>并不是中国重振增长和恢复正在消失的经济信心所需要的。</p><p>中国经济正面临<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-slips-into-deflation-in-warning-sign-for-world-economy-bbefb179?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">一系列挑战</a>，包括旷日持久的房地产紧缩、与以美国为首的西方国家关系恶化、以及在投资和出口等通常的增长引擎失灵的情况下难以培育消费拉动的经济扩张。</p><p>周二的数据显示，中国7月份的消费者支出、工业生产以及公共和私人投资指标大幅低于预期，加剧了经济方面的坏消息。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835679?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>与此同时，中国国家统计局宣布将暂停公布中国青年失业率数据，称计划重新审视统计方法。</p><p>对于投资者和经济学家来说，突然的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-data-security-law-ships-ports-court-cases-universities-11638803230?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">停顿符合中国经济关键方面日益模糊的令人担忧的模式</a>。他们警告说，正当北京方面大肆宣扬<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/xi-china-economy-capital-investment-3439d31a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">吸引外资的</a>重要性之际，北京<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-opaque-decision-making-confounds-business-governments-11673269970?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">方面压制信息流动的</a>举措可能会进一步打击本已脆弱的信心，并削弱中国作为投资目的地的吸引力。</p><p> “无论中国官员是否公布青年失业数据，都不会改变人们的看法，”北京精品投资银行 Chanson &amp; Co. 董事沉萌表示。 “隐瞒数据只会加剧市场对经济健康状况的担忧。”</p><p>近几个月来，中国当局加大了外国机构获取某些经济和金融数据的难度，包括公司注册信息、专利和某些统计数据。</p><p> 10月，中国国家统计局在季度国内生产总值数据即将发布前几个小时突然<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-economic-data-gets-harder-to-find-as-growth-slows-11666092169?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">停止发布</a>，但没有提供任何解释。几天前，在中共<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/frosted-windows-swarming-police-signal-start-of-chinas-big-conclave-11665928844?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">十年两次代表大会</a>的背景下，中国根本没有发布月度官方贸易数据。它最终公布了这些数据，但除了引用了未具体说明的“工作安排”外， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-economy-grew-3-9-in-the-third-quarter-11666576957?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">没有解释延迟的原因</a>。</p><p>资产管理公司 TCW Group 新兴市场董事总经理、前美国财政部官员戴维·洛文格 (David Loevinger) 表示，中国数据和政策制定透明度不断恶化，为投资世界第二大经济体“增加了另一层风险” 。</p><p> “我们都知道预测是困难的，尤其是对未来的预测，”他说。 “如果你不太确定现在发生了什么，那就更难了。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835741?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>中国还扩大了反间谍法，并<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-confirms-campaign-against-alleged-spying-by-foreign-consulting-companies-fef48e16?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">突击搜查了包括贝恩公司在内的国际商业咨询公司的办公室</a>，与中国当局会面的外国企业高管表示，这是北京方面对其他公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-ratchets-up-pressure-on-foreign-companies-524b958e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">施加更大控制的</a>努力的一部分。世界观中国。</p><p>近几个月来，中国青年失业率的飙升成为国内外<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-youth-unemployment-xi-jobs-522028c5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">关注</a>的焦点。根据最新的官方数据，6月份中国16至24岁城市地区超过五分之一（21.3%）的人失业，这说明中国经济中的问题日益严重。截至 12 月，这一数字为 16.7%。</p><p>经济学家预计，随着今年夏天最新一​​批毕业生完成学业，青年失业率将再次上升，统计局预计将于周二公布数据。</p><p>但那从未发生过。相反，中国国家统计局表示，将暂停发布这些数据，同时其统计人员将研究这些数据的编制方式，以及如果学生在找工作的同时仍在学习，是否应将其算作失业人员。如果学生积极寻找工作并符合其他标准，美国和其他国家/地区就会将其视为失业。</p><p>总体失业率的总体指标——城镇调查失业率自2月份以来首次上升，从7月份的5.2%升至5.3%。</p><p>周二的一批数据显示经济全面陷入困境。上周的数据显示，中国上个月的消费者价格同比下降，而家庭和企业的贷款需求却消失了。</p><p>在国际方面，第二季度中国的外国直接投资触及数十年来的最低水平，随着西方消费者在经济增长放缓和利率上升的情况下继续削减支出，出口大幅下滑。</p><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SCGLY" class="company-name">法国兴业银行的</a>经济学家在周二数据发布后给客户的一份报告中表示：“这个信息响亮而明确：中国正在经历全面通货紧缩。”他们列举了一系列恶化的指标，包括消费者和生产者价格、出口、投资和消耗。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835743?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>到目前为止，官员们的语气要乐观得多。周二，中国国家统计局发言人付令辉表示，中国尚未出现、今后也不会出现通货紧缩，重申了旨在消除人们对物价持续下跌担忧的官方言论。中国主要的国家晚间新闻广播称，最新数据显示经济基础稳定。</p><p>与今年前三个月相比，第二季度中国经济<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-economy-barely-grows-as-recovery-fades-5652a92a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">仅增长了0.8%</a> ，与去年同期（当时上海和其他城市受到封锁）相比，增长了6.3%，看起来更为健康。然而，对许多中国人来说，经济增长的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/for-many-in-china-it-feels-like-a-recession-25ce4b68" target="_blank" class="icon none">感觉比官方数据显示的黯淡得多</a>。</p><p>一些经济学家担心，如果不采取更强有力的行动扭转经济，中国可能会陷入增长疲软的螺旋式下降，因为企业和家庭信心低迷，导致支出、就业和投资进一步下滑。</p><p>周二，<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/BCS" class="company-name">巴克莱银行</a>将全年 GDP 预期从 4.9% 下调至 4.5%，理由是经济普遍疲软且缺乏有意义的刺激措施。该投资银行的新预测低于中国政策制定者今年约5%的官方GDP目标，许多经济学家认为这一目标保守且缺乏雄心。</p><p>政策制定者面临的一项特别紧迫的任务是挽救房地产行业，近年来该行业占中国经济总量的五分之一之多。六月和七月房屋销售大幅下滑，而中国最大的房地产巨头之一<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/HK/XHKG/2007" class="">碧桂园控股</a><span class="company-name-type">则</span><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-property-company-country-garden-holdings-default-risk-22b3bd64?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">面临债务违约风险上升</a>。</p><p>中国央行中国人民银行根据最新数据宣布一系列降息，下调银行短期和中期贷款利率，这些举措通常预示着银行将降低家庭和企业的借贷费用。</p><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NMR" class="company-name">野村</a>证券驻香港首席中国经济学家陆挺表示，货币宽松可能不足以阻止经济放缓。陆和其他经济学家表示，北京需要考虑采取更大胆的举措来重振摇曳的增长，例如支持陷入困境的房地产开发商，放松主要城市的购房限制以稳定房地产市场，或者向消费者开出支票以刺激支出。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> ——北京的肖晓和 Grace Zhu 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Jason Douglas（ <a href="mailto:jason.douglas@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jason.douglas@wsj.com）</a>和 Stella Yifan Xie（ <a href="mailto:stella.xie@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">stella.xie@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 15 Aug 2023 14:28:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-turns-to-well-honed-playbook-cut-rates-hide-data-bcfdd02</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-turns-to-well-honed-playbook-cut-rates-hide-data-bcfdd02<author><![CDATA[Jason DouglasStella Yifan Xie]]></author><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>经济增长/衰退</category><category>就业/失业数据</category><category>货币政策</category><category>利率</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>经济增长</category><category>经济衰退</category><category>就业</category><category>失业数字</category><category>货币政策</category><category>利率</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Americans Flocked to Cancún for Vacation. Now They’re Thinking Twice.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>这座墨西哥度假城市在 2021 年和 2022 年出现了激增，但游客的优先事项已经发生了变化<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001121949"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="578" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832622?width=860&amp;height=578" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">在坎昆地区运营的旅游公司正在短期内降低价格。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Elizabeth Ruiz/法新社，盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001121949"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/allison-pohle" itemprop="url" rel="author">艾莉森·波尔</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 15 日上午 10:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/cancun-mexico-travel-deals-safety-f5a49403"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>美国游客在阳光下享受乐趣，但他们的思考超越了坎昆等老地方。</p><p>今年春天，美国游客停止了前往坎昆和邻近的里维埃拉玛雅的旅行，将注意力转向<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/american-travelers-are-shunning-the-u-s-for-europe-5b5e08ea?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">欧洲、日本和加勒比海其他地区等目的地</a>。美国商务部国际贸易管理局<a href="https://www.trade.gov/data-visualization/apisi-92-monitor" target="_blank" class="icon none">的数据</a>显示，直飞墨西哥最大度假区坎昆的美国旅客数量与去年同期相比略有下降。酒店和航空公司表示，他们也注意到需求偶尔会下降。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>来自北卡罗来纳州夏洛特的 28 岁内容创作者凯拉·莫里斯 (Khayla Morris) 表示：“我有点厌倦了墨西哥。”莫里斯于 2022 年 5 月与姐妹们一起前往坎昆，并于 2017 年和 2018 年去过坎昆。</p><p>在坎昆地区运营的旅游公司正在降低短期价格，机票价格也较去年有所下降，因为航空公司都押注于长期并增加了航线。</p><h3>寻找其他地方</h3><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SAVE" class="company-name">Spirit Airlines</a>和 Playa Hotels and Resorts 的高管在最近的财报电话会议上表示，近几个月来坎昆及周边地区的需求出现波动。</p><p> Playa 首席财务官 Ryan Hymel 在公司财报电话会议上表示，这是由于“目的地疲劳”。他在电话中表示，墨西哥是 2021 年和 2022 年的目的地，但由于人们可以前往欧洲或其他加勒比地区旅行，因此不再是优先考虑的地方。 Playa 首席执行官 Bruce Wardinski 表示，游客在旺季有很多选择。</p><p>美国游客仍然喜欢墨西哥。坎昆和里维埃拉玛雅所在地墨西哥金塔纳罗奥州旅游局表示，与 2019 年前六个月相比，1 月至 6 月该地区的美国游客数量增加了约 12%。旅游局表示，这些数字代表了大流行时期增长的放缓，而不是美国游客市场的减少。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="527" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832869?width=700&amp;height=527" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">近几个月来，更多警察在坎昆巡逻。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：PAOLA CHIOMANTE/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>国际贸易管理局的数据显示，美国飞往坎昆的直达旅客数量在六月和七月有所回升，超过了上年同期。</p><p>许多美国游客在疫情爆发初期<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-mexico-vacation-during-the-pandemic-the-rewards-vs-risks-11610655230?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">就选择了墨西哥</a>。与其他主要目的地不同，该国不需要疫苗接种证明或新冠病毒检测呈阴性的证明即可入境。</p><p>墨西哥旅游商业委员会列举了今年春季美国游客数量下降的几个原因，其中包括<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/mexicos-peso-surges-to-strongest-level-since-2015-4286806?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">墨西哥比索升值</a>至近八年来的最高水平，这使得墨西哥对国际游客来说更加昂贵。其他因素包括来自其他目的地的更多竞争以及旅行者对安全的担忧。</p><p>近年来，与毒品有关的暴力导致墨西哥部分地区的凶杀率<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/cancun-tulum-riviera-maya-mexico-drugs-homicides-11648853578?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">达到创纪录水平</a>。近几个月来，更多警察开始在坎昆巡逻。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>你在坎昆度假吗？为什么或者为什么不？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>现代旅游专业公司（Modern Travel Professionals）的老板克里斯汀·哈登伯格（Christine Hardenberger）表示，由于暴力事件的报道，度假者对前往坎昆旅行感到更加焦虑，但许多人最终还是去了那里，因为他们住在以游客为中心的酒店区和里维埃拉玛雅。他们发现，与其他国际目的地相比，他们的花费要多得多，尤其是在全包式度假村。</p><h3>期待便宜货</h3><p>高档 Viceroy Riviera Maya 的销售营销总监图利奥·巴鲁克 (Tulio Baruch) 表示，随着酒店争夺业务，今年秋天游客应该会迎来优惠。</p><p>最大的消费者往往对价格不太敏感。凯悦首席执行官 Mark Hoplamazian 表示，在坎昆里维埃拉玛雅市场，五星级酒店的表现比四星级酒店高出 10 个百分点。他引用了凯悦旗下 ALG Vacations 的数据，该公司是一家度假套餐公司，旗下品牌包括 CheapCaribbean.com 和 Southwest Vacations 等。</p><p>但一些五星级度假村的游客人数有所下降。巴鲁克表示，上季度美国游客在维瑟罗里维埃拉玛雅酒店预订的客房数量比去年同期减少了 15%。他说，度假者选择了意大利、希腊和日本。</p><p>巴鲁克表示，近年来该地区开设了许多新的豪华度假村。他说，需求下降和供应增加意味着酒店必须降低房价。他说，上个季度，前往他的度假村的美国游客每晚支付约 626 美元，比去年同期便宜 45 美元。</p><p>根据旅游搜索引擎 Kayak 的数据，本月飞往坎昆的平均往返经济舱机票价格为 424 美元，比去年下降 10%。</p><p>该航空公司执行副总裁兼首席商务官马特·克莱因 (Matt Klein) 表示，即使价格较高，精神航空 4 月份飞往坎昆的航班也已售罄。但他在公司财报电话会议上表示，与去年同期相比，六月份的收入下降了“非常高的两位数”。 “需求刚刚下降，”他说。精神航空降低了票价以解决客流下降的问题。</p><p>许多旅游高管认为需求下降是暂时的，并通过增加航班运力来押注长期利益。美国联合航空公司 (United Airlines) 最近表示，将从 10 月底开始使用大型<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/BA" class="company-name">波音</a>777-200 飞机执飞飞往坎昆的 3 条航线。</p><p>夏洛特的内容创作者莫里斯表示，由于通货膨胀，她正在更加密切地关注自己的资金。她计划今年春天返回坎昆参加婚礼，但会优先考虑其他海滩目的地，例如特克斯和凯科斯群岛。</p><p> “如果我要花这么多钱，我就会去我真正想去的地方，”她说。</p><p><em>订阅新的</em> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/newsletters?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none"><em>《华尔街日报》旅游通讯，</em></a><em>了解《华尔街日报》旅游团队的更多提示和见解。</em></p><p class="articleTagLine"> —<em>安东尼·哈鲁普</em>对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Allison Pohle，邮箱为<a href="mailto:allison.pohle@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">allison.pohle@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 15 Aug 2023 14:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/cancun-mexico-travel-deals-safety-f5a49403</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/cancun-mexico-travel-deals-safety-f5a49403<author><![CDATA[Allison Pohle]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>住宿/餐厅/酒吧</category><category>住宿</category><category>酒店/汽车旅馆</category><category>信托/基金/金融工具</category><category>私人产权</category><category>另类投资</category><category>金融服务</category><category>投资/证券</category><category>休闲/艺术/酒店</category><category>旅游</category><category>风险投资</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>消费者优惠</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>个人财务</category><category>消费者支出/预算</category><category>旅游优惠/套餐</category><category>旅行</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>内华达普拉亚酒店及度假村</category><category>普拉亚</category><category>凯悦酒店</category><category>H</category><category>精神航空</category><category>节省</category><category>瑞安·海梅尔</category><category>布鲁斯·瓦尔丁斯基</category><category>马克·霍普拉马齐安</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>消费者优惠</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>个人财务</category><category>消费支出</category><category>预算编制</category><category>旅游优惠</category><category>包</category><category>旅行</category><category>住宿</category><category>餐馆</category><category>酒吧</category><category>酒店</category><category>汽车旅馆</category><category>信托</category><category>资金</category><category>金融工具</category><category>私人产权</category><category>另类投资</category><category>金融服务</category><category>投资</category><category>证券</category><category>闲暇</category><category>艺术</category><category>款待</category><category>旅游</category><category>风险投资</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Brutal Heat Tests Ability of Energy Exporters to Keep Their Citizens Cool]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>不断飙升的电力需求正在压垮整个中东老化的电力网络<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001135592"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="607" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834890?width=860&amp;height=607" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">开罗停电引发人们对该市国内天然气供应不足的担忧。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：AMR ABDALLAH DALSH/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001135592"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/chao-deng" itemprop="url" rel="author">邓超</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 15 日上午 7:48 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/brutal-summer-heat-tests-ability-of-energy-exporters-to-keep-their-citizens-cool-6cc07445"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>开罗——中东和北非能源丰富的国家在酷暑期间努力维持本国居民的电力供应，埃及是最新实行轮流停电的国家。</p><p>这里的停电引发了人们对开罗<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/egypt-dims-the-lights-in-cairo-to-free-up-more-gas-for-europe-11668681057?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">国内天然气供应</a>不足的担忧。</p><p>伊朗和伊拉克这两个石油出口国也面临着停电，因为该地区气温极高，巴格达的气温高达 122 华氏度<strong>，</strong>老化的电网不堪重负。</p><p>由于空调、冰箱和风扇缺乏电力，本月巴格达街头引发了小规模抗议活动。同样，在伊朗的一些城市，上个月的用电量创下历史新高，近几周的需求压力导致电网崩溃。</p><p>伊朗政府关闭银行和公共办公室两天，以阻止居民<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/iran-begins-two-day-shutdown-as-heat-wave-worsens-e756dcfc?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在炎热的天气外出</a>，官员们敦促人们减少用电。</p><p> In Egypt, analysts say that extreme summer temperatures have been exacerbated by a lack of maintenance of some power stations, rising demand from a fast-growing population and falling output at the country&#39;s largest gas field.</p><p> “It&#39;s very likely that Egypt has a shortage in gas,” said Timothy Kaldas, deputy director of the Tahrir Institute for Middle East Policy, a Washington-based nonprofit. “Production is down and there are no exports at a time when they&#39;re desperate to export.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="502" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835729?width=700&amp;height=502" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Egyptian President Abdel Fattah Al Sisi, center, and other officials looking at mockups of natural-gas facilities in 2018.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: handout/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The Egyptian government denies it is facing a gas shortage and says power cuts are necessary because of rocketing demand during the heat wave. Blackouts this summer have been especially painful. Temperatures topped 114 degrees Fahrenheit in late July, according to the Egyptian Meteorological Authority.</p><p> Still, the country&#39;s gas exports, which peaked in December, according to commodities data firm Kpler, fell to zero in June and rose only slightly in July.</p><p> Problems with power and gas supplies were among the grievances that contributed to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887323899704578583191518313964?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the downfall</a> of President Mohammed Morsi in 2013. Electricity outages persisted after President Abdel Fattah Al Sisi came to power, leading him to spend enormous sums to increase the capacity of the country&#39;s power network. The 2015 discovery of a mammoth gas field in the Mediterranean, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bp-to-buy-10-stake-in-enis-giant-zohr-gas-field-off-egypt-coast-1480095283?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">known as Zohr</a> , allowed Egypt at one point to increase gas production and decrease imports.</p><p> But pressure by the government to accelerate the development of Zohr caused water infiltration problems that have persisted and which are in part responsible for lower gas output this year, according to Egyptian officials familiar with the matter.<br><br> In a <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=m2_bBeTujfY" target="_blank" class="icon none">speech</a> in October, Sisi said that he had told <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/E" class="company-name">Eni</a> —one of the developers of the Zohr gas field—it had 18 months to develop the reservoir, compared with the five-year timeline the Italian firm had proposed. <strong>&nbsp;</strong></p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>What further consequences could arise from a gas shortage in Egypt?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Egyptian gas output will likely fall to a <a href="https://www.fitchsolutions.com/oil-gas/declining-gas-production-egypt-underlines-need-further-discoveries-18-07-2023?fSWebArticleValidation=true&amp;mkt_tok=NzMyLUNLSC03NjcAAAGNewGSpgjRphyEmHgXsKqcU1Hw3j8KQZmQh6MbqJXYB2SdmamMwOR0gaEP-3ipAytil2KuktxcI45KahM09IkuYum0Z9niAvi0GIeSVoVngg" target="_blank" class="icon none">new three-year low</a> of 64.9 billion cubic meters this year, according to BMI, a subsidiary of credit-ratings firm Fitch, amid “ongoing water infiltration issues” at Zohr. The field has produced about 40% of the country&#39;s total gas output in recent years.</p><p> Eni and the Egyptian government say it isn&#39;t true that technical problems at Zohr have caused a decline in production capacity.</p><p> “A number of projects [are] now running to improve the processing capacity and…to ultimately sustain the production,” a spokesman for the Oil Ministry said about Zohr.</p><p> Cairo is now exploring whether Israel can pipe more natural gas to Egypt, according to some of the officials.</p><p> Israel <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/eu-signs-gas-deal-with-israel-egypt-in-bid-to-wean-itself-off-russian-supplies-11655299886?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">agreed last year</a> to step up gas exports to Egypt for the purpose of liquefying it for re-export to Europe. But when Israeli Energy Minister</p> Israel Katz said this month that his country would increase its own exports, he said that Egypt was facing “a serious crisis” and needed more gas for local consumption.<p></p><p> In poorer parts of Egypt, including in the south, households say electricity cuts are lasting for hours and some complain of lack of water because their water pumps also rely on electricity. Other Egyptians say that outages aren&#39;t equally dispersed and don&#39;t affect wealthy coastal towns of the north including Alamein, where Sisi and the country&#39;s elite are known to spend the summers.</p><p> The prime minister&#39;s office said in a statement on Facebook last month that authorities&#39; power-saving plan excluded three coastal governorates, including where Alamein is located, because of what it said were low consumption rates there.</p><p> In the northern city of Port Said, Dina Tal&#39;at blamed the heat during power outages for her 5-year-old son&#39;s vomiting. The family lost electricity for more than two days, leaving much of the food in their fridge to rot as temperatures became unbearable. When the power did come back on, it was only for three hours.<br><br> “I have never ever seen such a disregard for the average citizen,” Tal&#39;at said of the government.</p><p> Mina Rafaat, a teacher living on the outskirts of Cairo, said her elderly mother fainted after the electricity in their home went off for five hours, leaving them without air conditioning.</p><p> “It&#39;s really tough,” she said. “I&#39;m afraid that this will happen to her again since this crisis seems to be persisting.”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Summer Said, Menna Farouk and Ahmed Medhat contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Chao Deng at <a href="mailto:chao.deng@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">chao.deng@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 15 Aug 2023 11:48:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/brutal-summer-heat-tests-ability-of-energy-exporters-to-keep-their-citizens-cool-6cc07445</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/brutal-summer-heat-tests-ability-of-energy-exporters-to-keep-their-citizens-cool-6cc07445<author><![CDATA[Chao Deng]]></author><category>活力</category><category>Oil and Gas Upstream Operations</category><category> Natural Gas Extraction</category><category> Oil and Natural Gas Exploration</category><category>化石燃料</category><category>Natural Gas</category><category>油和气</category><category>Blackouts</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>灾害/事故</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> blackouts</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>灾难</category><category>事故</category><category>活力</category><category>oil and gas upstream operations</category><category> natural gas extraction</category><category> oil and natural gas exploration</category><category>化石燃料</category><category>natural gas</category><category>油和气</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Russia Launches Emergency Rate Rise to Stem Economic Turmoil]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Ruble&#39;s recent slide reflects growing uncertainties as Russia battles inflation, sanctions, labor shortages <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001135495"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835219?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Elvira Nabiullina, chair of Russia&#39;s central bank, which raised rates by 3.5 percentage points on Tuesday.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Alexander Kulebyakin/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001135495"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/georgi-kantchev" itemprop="url" rel="author">Georgi Kantchev</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/chelsey-dulaney" itemprop="url" rel="author">Chelsey Dulaney</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated Aug. 15, 2023 6:38 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-imposes-emergency-interest-rate-rise-to-halt-ruble-selloff-f3668bd1"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Russia&#39;s central bank jacked up its key interest rate at an emergency meeting to stem a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russian-ruble-at-weakest-level-since-early-days-of-ukraine-war-eaef275f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">sharp selloff in the ruble</a> and resurgent inflation, a response to the mounting financial costs of Moscow&#39;s war in Ukraine.</p><p> The bank on Tuesday raised the rate to 12% from 8.5%, a day after the currency temporarily fell past 100 to the US dollar for the first time since the weeks after Russia invaded Ukraine. The ruble recovered somewhat in anticipation of the decision but remains down by nearly a quarter this year, placing it among the world&#39;s worst-performing currencies.</p><p> While it fell into a recession last year, the Russian economy was able to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-west-attacked-russias-economy-the-result-is-another-stalemate-99ec913b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">weather the wave of Western sanctions</a> thanks to a windfall of oil-and-gas revenues, hefty government stimulus and the country&#39;s swift ability to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-defies-sanctions-by-selling-oil-above-price-cap-bae1c271?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">divert trade from Europe to Asia</a> .</p><p> But the ruble&#39;s recent slide is an indication that the interlude of relative stability in the economy has passed. Russia is caught between fast-rising inflation and a government that needs to borrow and spend to keep up the war effort in Ukraine, a toxic mix for the economy. It also faces the mounting impact of sanctions and a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russias-big-economic-problem-not-enough-workers-d5164d47?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">drastic labor shortage</a> .</p><p> Russia&#39;s macroeconomic stability is “now in a more vulnerable position than at any point since the early stages of the war,” said Liam Peach, senior emerging-market economist at Capital Economics. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835687?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Fast-rising imports and slower exports this year, coupled with capital outflows and political uncertainty in the aftermath of the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/wagner-prigozhin-putin-mutiny-moscow-march-7072d6e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">aborted Wagner mutiny</a> in June have all pushed the ruble lower in recent weeks.</p><p> The ruble&#39;s decline, analysts say, points to a growing realization: The war and Russia&#39;s isolation will drag on, possibly for years. Such a scenario envisions Russia&#39;s economy pinned down by an expanded military footprint and Western sanctions for the long term.</p><p> “The ruble fall reflects the fundamental imbalance in the Russian economy because of the war,” said Alexandra Prokopenko, a former Russian central-bank official who is now a nonresident scholar at the Berlin-based Carnegie Russia Eurasia Center. “Fundamentally the central bank rate can&#39;t change the trend.”</p><p> For Russia&#39;s economy, a longer war means higher inflation as the government spends more on weapons and social measures to placate the population at home. A weaker ruble makes imports more expensive.</p><p> Prolonged sanctions mean that Russia&#39;s international supply chains will remain disrupted, adding further pressure on prices. Currently, Russia is able to import many of the goods that the West has banned—from iPhones to cars to computer chips—but it does so via third countries, a roundabout that increases prices.</p><p> “Inflationary pressure is building up,” the central bank said. “The pass-through of the ruble&#39;s depreciation to prices is gaining momentum and inflation expectations are on the rise.”</p><p> The central bank&#39;s move on Tuesday follows a larger-than-expected <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-raises-rates-as-ukraine-war-costs-mount-a41bfa23?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">rate increase in July</a> . The bank&#39;s next planned meeting is in September.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>What&#39;s next for the Russian economy?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> For the Kremlin, the deterioration in the economy presents a fresh set of challenges as its military fights off Ukrainian advances in the field of battle. Long wars are often won and lost based on the ability of nations to maintain and project economic strength. Western nations have spent billions of dollars to shore up Ukraine&#39;s economy and supply its war effort.</p><p> The central bank has attributed the ruble&#39;s decline to the country&#39;s deteriorating trade position. Moscow sells its crude at a discount to global prices and has stopped natural-gas deliveries to much of Europe, traditionally its biggest market.</p><p> Russia&#39;s current-account surplus, a broad measure of funds flowing into the economy, shrank to $25.2 billion in the first seven months of the year, an 85% fall compared with the same period last year, central-bank data showed last week.</p><p> Some of the weakening in Russia&#39;s trade position stems from an increased reliance on imports from places like China and Turkey. In Russia&#39;s war economy, domestic demand has outstripped Russia&#39;s capacity to produce, particularly in industries that have been hit by the withdrawal of Western firms and sanctions. Russian imports of goods rose 18% in the first seven months of 2023 compared with a year earlier.</p><p> Political turmoil will also continue to undermine the ruble as the war drags on. The currency&#39;s slow decline since the start of the year picked up pace after the Wagner mutiny created uncertainty around President <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/vladimir-putin">Vladimir Putin</a> &#39;s</p> grip on power. <p></p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835689?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> The currency&#39;s gyrations have also provided a rare window into the tensions between the government and the central bank over how to manage the economy. A senior Kremlin aide on Monday blamed the weak ruble on loose monetary policy.</p><p> Some saw the public finger-pointing as a sign that tensions have continued to build within Russian political circles since the failed mutiny led by Yevgeny Prigozhin, the leader of the Wagner mercenary group, in late June.</p><p> “This may be an extension of the elite battles, like with Prigozhin and Wagner, to the economic technocrats in the administration,” said Timothy Ash, a senior emerging-market strategist at BlueBay Asset Management. “It shows generally a lack of confidence in leadership at the top.”</p><p> A loss of confidence is a major risk to the value of the ruble. Russians withdrew roughly $1 billion from Russia&#39;s banks in the days after the Wagner mutiny, adding to a steady stream of outflows since the war began as they opt for cash and stash money abroad. The ruble&#39;s decline, the rise in inflation and growing political division all could encourage more capital flight, which would in turn fuel more pressure on the ruble, analysts say.</p><p> Another option for the Kremlin to steady the ruble: the reimposition of capital controls to prop up demand for rubles. That formula of much higher rates and restrictions on money leaving the country helped stabilize the ruble after it plunged in the months after the start of the war in 2022.</p><p> “In the short term they can slow the bleeding with large rate hikes like this but it doesn&#39;t fundamentally alter the picture for the ruble,” said Peach of Capital Economics. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=1DFAFAD1-8AAF-44B7-B265-599DD90D1C97&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Frussia-imposes-emergency-interest-rate-rise-to-halt-ruble-selloff-f3668bd1&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> As the West scrambles to move away from Russian energy sources and imposes sanctions on Moscow, China and India have stepped in to fill the gap. WSJ examines how those countries have boosted Russia&#39;s revenue from oil sales, supporting its economy. Photo illustration: Sharon Shi<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Higher rates will make it more attractive for local savers to keep their money in rubles, but it will also weigh on Russia&#39;s already-muted economic growth by driving up the cost to borrow and investment.</p><p> There is another complication: It will also make it more expensive for the Russian government to service its domestic debt. The government has gone on a borrowing binge over the past year to make up the gap in revenues from discounted oil sales. Much of that debt, issued as local government bonds, has been issued with floating rates.</p><p> While Russia&#39;s headline inflation rate appears moderate, at 4.3% year-over-year in July, that is a sharp increase from the 2.5% rate in May. Much of the increase in prices is masked by the high comparison base from the post-invasion shock last year. Inflation over the past three months amounted to 7.6% on average in seasonally adjusted annualized terms, the central bank said Tuesday.</p><p> The falling currency has pushed up the prices of items such as appliances, cars and fruit that depend on imports, the central bank said Monday. Rising prices are an added worry for the government ahead of presidential elections slated for March.</p><p> Write to Georgi Kantchev at <a href="mailto:georgi.kantchev@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">georgi.kantchev@wsj.com</a> and Chelsey Dulaney at <a href="mailto:chelsey.dulaney@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">chelsey.dulaney@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 15 Aug 2023 10:38:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-imposes-emergency-interest-rate-rise-to-halt-ruble-selloff-f3668bd1</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-imposes-emergency-interest-rate-rise-to-halt-ruble-selloff-f3668bd1<author><![CDATA[Georgi KantchevChelsey Dulaney]]></author><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>Inflation Figures/Price Indices</category><category>货币政策</category><category>利率</category><category>贸易/外部支付</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>International Relations</category><category> International Sanctions</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>贸易壁垒/限制</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>inflation figures</category><category> price indices</category><category>货币政策</category><category>利率</category><category>贸易</category><category>外部支付</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>international sanctions</category><category>政治</category><category>贸易壁垒</category><category>限制</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Donald Trump Indicted in Georgia Over Effort to Overturn Election Results]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Charges brought by Fulton County&#39;s district attorney mark fourth criminal case against former president <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831598/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="2024 年共和党总统提名的领跑者、前总统唐纳德·特朗普否认有不当行为。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Former President Donald Trump, the front-runner for the 2024 Republican presidential nomination, denies wrongdoing. Melissa Sue Gerrits/Getty Images <span>Melissa Sue Gerrits/Getty Images</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001116987"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001116987"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/cameron-mcwhirter" itemprop="url" rel="author">Cameron McWhirter</a></span> , <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jan-wolfe" itemprop="url" rel="author">Jan Wolfe</a></span> , <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/aruna-viswanatha" itemprop="url" rel="author">Aruna Viswanatha</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sadie-gurman" itemprop="url" rel="author">Sadie Gurman</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated Aug. 15, 2023 1:22 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-indicted-georgia-election-interference-case-64deb461"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> ATLANTA—A grand jury here charged <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">Donald Trump</a> , Rudy Giuliani and other Trump allies with operating a criminal enterprise that sought to overturn <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/joe-biden">Joe Biden</a> &#39;s electoral victory in Georgia, marking the fourth time the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-guide-to-donald-trumps-legal-perils-b9b64891?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">former president has been indicted</a> this year and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-new-charges-facing-donald-trump-and-how-he-might-defend-himself-53a2b45?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">deepening his legal woes</a> ahead of the 2024 election.</p><p> There were 19 people in total <a href="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/documents/GATRUMPINDICTMENT081423.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">charged in the indictment</a> , including former Trump White House chief of staff Mark Meadows and legal adviser Sidney Powell.</p><p> Taken together, the Georgia charges allege a sweeping criminal conspiracy to overturn the 2020 election result and undermine US democracy. They describe calls, emails, and other efforts to allegedly press state and federal officials into backing the effort to find votes Trump lacked to win or assert that he was victorious both in Georgia and other states he lost.</p><p> The sprawling indictment, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fani-willis-the-no-nonsense-georgia-prosecutor-on-a-collision-course-with-donald-trump-600b88f8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">brought by</a> Fulton County District Attorney Fani Willis, covers some of the same ground as the federal case Trump faces in Washington, but goes into greater detail on the effort in Georgia and offers some new elements of the alleged conspiracy. It charges Trump with 13 felonies, alleging he pushed false claims of voter fraud in Georgia and pressured Republican officials to help him secure the state&#39;s Electoral College votes. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=63AF554A-ED80-41F6-BE4D-ADF5F7ECFA84&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fdonald-trump-indicted-georgia-election-interference-case-64deb461&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Former president Donald Trump is facing four separate indictments at both state and federal levels. WSJ breaks down each of the indictments and what they mean for his 2024 presidential campaign. Photo Illustration: Annie Zhao<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Willis, whose investigation lasted more than two years, used the state&#39;s sweeping antiracketeering law to describe an elaborate plot to stay in power over the will of Georgia voters. Biden narrowly won the state in 2020.</p><p> “The defendants engaged in a criminal racketeering enterprise to overturn Georgia&#39;s presidential election results,” Willis said during a press conference late Monday, adding that the defendants pursued an illegal goal of allowing Trump to seize a presidential term.</p><p> She said she would seek a trial date in the next six months. She gave the defendants until Friday, Aug. 25, to turn themselves in.</p><p> Trump, on his Truth Social platform, declared the investigation a witch hunt. “Why didn&#39;t they Indict 2.5 years ago? Because they wanted to do it right in the middle of my political campaign,” he said.</p><p> Trump&#39;s lawyers issued a statement that said in part, “We look forward to a detailed review of this indictment which is undoubtedly just as flawed and unconstitutional as this entire process has been.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="896" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/a7dc45f6-d690-4f27-9034-c24e2929ee1d-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> The indictment details 161 separate acts it says were undertaken as part of the conspiracy to reverse the election outcome, beginning with a speech Trump gave declaring victory the day after the presidential election. It also alleges that the criminal enterprise operated in Georgia outside of Fulton County as well as in other states, including Michigan, Arizona, Pennsylvania, Nevada and New Mexico.</p><p> The indictment alleges Giuliani led the effort in battleground states, including Georgia, to keep Trump in power. Giuliani called the indictment “an affront to American Democracy” and said it does “permanent, irrevocable harm to our justice system.”</p><p> Several individuals are charged with breaching voting machines in Coffee County, a rural county about 200 miles from Atlanta. Those defendants, including Powell, were charged with conspiracy to commit computer theft. Powell had pushed false claims that voting machines had been hacked to flip votes from Trump to Biden.</p><p> Willis also indicted John Eastman and Kenneth Chesebro, who argued in legal memos that then-Vice President <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/mike-pence">Mike Pence</a> could block Electoral College votes from being certified.</p><p> Other defendants include Jenna Ellis, a former Trump lawyer, and</p> Jeffrey Clark, a Trump administration Justice Department official who urged his colleagues to launch investigations in Georgia based on Trump&#39;s unsupported claims of voting fraud. A lawyer for Ellis didn&#39;t immediately return calls for comment.<p></p><p> “ Jeff Clark was simply doing his job in 2020 and he doesn&#39;t deserve to be subjected to this naked political lawfare, especially not by a publicity hound like Willis,” said Rachel Cauley, a spokeswoman for Center for Renewing America, the conservative think tank where Clark works. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=1F164012-9314-4C51-AF75-113013B9D8A3&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fdonald-trump-indicted-georgia-election-interference-case-64deb461&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Fulton County District Attorney Fani Willis announced 41 counts against former President Donald Trump and 18 other people for operating a criminal enterprise that sought to overturn the 2020 election in Georgia. Photo: John Bazemore/Associated Press<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Lawyers for Eastman, Meadows, Chesebro and Powell didn&#39;t immediately respond to requests for comment.</p><p> Three other defendants charged were “fake electors” or “alternate electors,” individuals who signed a certificate falsely stating that Trump had won Georgia in the 2020 election and declared themselves the state&#39;s “duly elected and qualified” electors.</p><p> Elsewhere, political reaction split along usual partisan lines.</p><p> House Speaker Kevin McCarthy (R., Calif.) in a tweet late Monday accused Willis of attacking Trump to advance her own political career.</p><p> Rep. Elise Stefanik of New York, a member of House GOP leadership, said: “President Trump had every legal right to challenge the results of the election” and accused Willis of bias.</p><p> Rep. Nikema Williams (D., Ga.), who also serves as chair of Georgia Democrats, said Trump had assaulted democracy by trying to disenfranchise Georgia voters because he didn&#39;t like the result of the 2020 election. “Now, Donald Trump is facing the consequences of his actions,” Williams said.</p><p> The indictment also charged several of the defendants with filing false documents, in some cases by sending the false elector certificates, and, in the case of Trump and Eastman, by filing a New Year&#39;s Eve lawsuit in federal court that included alleged lies such as that thousands of minors and dead people voted in the 2020 election.</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> In addition to the 19 defendants, the indictment describes a further 30 people as unindicted co-conspirators, leaving open the possibility of additional charges in connection with the case.</p><p> The move by Willis, a Democrat, had been widely anticipated. In April, she said she planned to announce charging decisions this summer, and she had told local law-enforcement leaders to prepare for the “significant public reaction” her announcement could trigger.</p><p> Willis opened the probe on the basis of a recorded Jan. 2, 2021, phone call in which then-President Trump urged Republican Brad Raffensperger, Georgia&#39;s top elections official, to find enough votes to overturn the election. Trump, the front-runner for the 2024 Republican presidential nomination, denies wrongdoing and has said the call was perfect.</p><p> Willis convened a special grand jury, which heard from more than 75 witnesses, wrote a report summarizing its findings and recommended criminal charges against several people whose identities haven&#39;t been made public. The special grand jury lacked the authority to issue indictments, however, prompting Willis to present evidence to a regular grand jury.</p><p> In November 2020, Trump lost the election in Georgia to Biden by roughly 12,000 votes out of five million cast. Trump and his supporters claimed the election was stolen, but statewide recounts and a partial forensic audit overseen by state election officials found no evidence of widespread fraud. Court challenges failed. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831333?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The indictment brought by Fulton County District Attorney Fani Willis alleges the former president pushed false claims of voter fraud and pressured Republican officials to help him secure Georgia&#39;s Electoral College votes.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：布林·安德森/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>The Monday indictment also outlines multiple episodes involving Meadows, who was the White House chief of staff when Trump tried to overturn the 2020 election result. Meadows featured minimally in the federal election-interference case and wasn&#39;t identifiable as one of the six unindicted co-conspirators in that case, where Trump is the only defendant.</p><p> The new indictment levels two charges against Meadows related to the alleged conspiracy, saying he attended meetings where Trump allegedly brought up lies about election fraud and he worked to arrange Trump calls with state officials to further the efforts, including the call during which Trump asked Georgia officials to find him more votes.</p><p> The indictment also describes a meeting at which Trump and Meadows allegedly asked Trump aide John McEntee to prepare a memo on how to disrupt or delay Congress&#39;s Jan. 6 counting of the electoral votes. And it charges both Trump and Meadows with trying to get Raffensperger to violate his oath of public office by pressuring him to change the results there.</p><p> Earlier this year, Trump was indicted by Manhattan District Attorney Alvin Bragg over the payment of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/grand-jury-votes-to-indict-donald-trump-a9512240?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">hush money to a porn star</a> on the eve of the 2016 election, marking the first time a former president has <a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/donald-trump-indictment-arrest-da-bragg?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">faced criminal charges</a> .</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>How will the latest charges against Donald Trump play out?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Then in June, federal prosecutors led by special counsel Jack Smith unsealed <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-federal-case-against-trump-on-the-mar-a-lago-documents-12054f5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a sweeping indictment</a> alleging the former president <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-indicted-in-document-case-b4e563d7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">held on to classified documents</a> he knew he shouldn&#39;t have retained access to, shared them with others and directed his staff to help him evade authorities&#39; efforts to get them back. The case is being handled in Florida.</p><p> A superseding federal indictment returned in late July charged Trump with three additional counts, including one of willful <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-lawyers-jack-smith-jan-6-58c2fd14?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">retention of national-defense information</a> , stemming from a classified national-security document prosecutors said he showed to visitors at his golf club in New Jersey.</p><p> Trump was indicted a third time Aug. 1 in a further criminal case accusing him of trying to subvert the will of American voters through his attempts to cling to power after he lost the 2020 election. <a href="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/documents/trumpindictment080123.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">That indictment</a> , by a federal grand jury in Washington, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-new-charges-facing-donald-trump-and-how-he-might-defend-himself-53a2b45?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">charges Trump with four crimes</a> , including conspiring to defraud the US, obstructing an official proceeding and conspiring against the rights of voters by his actions that culminated in the Jan. 6, 2021, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-protesters-are-in-the-building-inside-the-capitol-stormed-by-a-pro-trump-mob-11609984654?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">attack by his supporters</a> on the US Capitol.</p><p> Trump pleaded not guilty in the New York, Florida and Washington, DC, cases. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/537f22eb-7442-4360-8305-39f89aae3339.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p class="articleTagLine"> —Byron Tau, Alex Leary, Lindsay Wise and Isaac Yu contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Cameron McWhirter at <a href="mailto:Cameron.McWhirter@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Cameron.McWhirter@wsj.com</a> , Jan Wolfe at <a href="mailto:jan.wolfe@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jan.wolfe@wsj.com</a> , Aruna Viswanatha at <a href="mailto:aruna.viswanatha@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">aruna.viswanatha@wsj.com</a> and Sadie Gurman at <a href="mailto:sadie.gurman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">sadie.gurman@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 15 Aug 2023 05:22:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-indicted-georgia-election-interference-case-64deb461</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-indicted-georgia-election-interference-case-64deb461<author><![CDATA[Cameron McWhirterJan WolfeAruna ViswanathaSadie Gurman]]></author><category> trump legal</category><category>华尔街日报-美国新闻</category><category>gfx-contrib</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>犯罪企业</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家/总统选举</category><category>Trump Legal</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>犯罪企业</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>总统选举</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Wall Street Is Ready to Scoop Up Commercial Real Estate on the Cheap]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Firms are raising billions of dollars for funds to target assets with slumping values <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833597/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="Vacancy rates in the office market have soared amid a sluggish return-to-the-office pace." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Vacancy rates in the office market have soared amid a sluggish return-to-the-office pace. BRENDAN MCDERMID/REUTERS <span>BRENDAN MCDERMID/REUTERS</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001133014"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001133014"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/peter-grant" itemprop="url" rel="author">Peter Grant</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated Aug. 15, 2023 12:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/wall-street-is-ready-to-scoop-up-commercial-real-estateon-the-cheap-6edac64f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Wall Street firms are raising new funds to acquire <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-return-to-the-office-has-stalled-e0af9741?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">office buildings</a> , apartments and other troubled commercial real estate, looking to scoop up properties at a fraction of the price investors paid a few years ago.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CNS" class="">Cohen &amp; Steers</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/GS" class="">Goldman Sachs</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> EQT Exeter and BGO, formerly known as BentallGreenOak, are among the prominent names raising billions of dollars for funds to target distressed assets and other real estate with slumping values, according to regulatory filings.</p><p> “The last few weeks, I&#39;ve been saying, &#39;holy mackerel, they&#39;re coming out of the woodwork,&#39;” said Kevin Gannon, chief executive of Robert A. Stanger &amp; Co., an investment-banking firm that tracks real-estate fundraising. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=88CDF171-D046-4FD4-A4BB-72130DCCB4C6&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fwall-street-is-ready-to-scoop-up-commercial-real-estateon-the-cheap-6edac64f&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> With housing in short supply, developers are converting more empty offices into apartments. But not all buildings are candidates for reuse, even as more than one billion square feet of office space sits vacant across the US Photo Illustration: Amber Bragdon<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>The new funds are seeking to capitalize on one of the most troubled commercial-property markets in decades. Values have nosedived since interest rates spiked last year, driving up borrowing costs in the highly leveraged business. The office market, one of the largest sectors, has also been clobbered by a sluggish return-to-office rate, which has sent vacancy rates soaring. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-real-estate-haven-turns-perilous-with-roughly-1-trillion-coming-due-74d20528?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Apartment buildings</a> , an investor haven in the past, look vulnerable as owners try to refinance at much higher rates. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/local-malls-stuck-in-death-spiral-plunge-in-value-a7998b7d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">Mall owners are contending with</a> steep value declines, some of more than 70% over the past few years.</p><p> Commercial-property sales have been moribund until recently because most sellers haven&#39;t been willing to cut their prices to the levels that buyers are demanding. Now, a small but growing number of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/rise-in-distressed-sales-signals-new-chapter-for-beleaguered-office-market-bbff313c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">office owners have begun to capitulate</a> , unloading distressed properties.</p><p> The capitulation marks a new phase in the commercial real-estate upheaval, as more beleaguered property owners turn over properties to lenders or decide to take what they can get, rather than hold out hope for an eventual recovery. This wave of fundraising is the latest sign that sales activity is expected to increase as more sellers yield on price. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="827" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834573?width=639&amp;height=827" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Developer Presidio Bay purchased a San Francisco office tower for $41 million, compared with its 2014 sales price of $107 million.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Jeff Peters</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> In one recent example, the owner of a downtown San Francisco office tower unloaded the property for $41 million to developer Presidio Bay. The seller, Clarion Partners, had purchased the property for $107 million in 2014.</p><p> While the clearest distress is in the office sector, many property owners with floating-rate debt may also feel pressured to sell at marked-down prices because they are unable to refinance at today&#39;s higher rates. In addition, fund managers expect values to fall as regional banks, under pressure from this year&#39;s <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bank-collapse-crisis-timeline-724f6458?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">rash of bank failures</a> , unload commercial-property loan portfolios at discounted prices.</p><p> “There are selective opportunities beginning to arise for investors that are in a position to take advantage of weakness,” said Rich Hill,</p> head of real-estate strategy for Cohen &amp; Steers, which is aiming to raise more than $2.5 billion in a new nontraded real-estate investment trust.<p></p><p> Commercial-property values already have fallen about 10 to 15 percentage points from their peaks in the third quarter last year, and might fall a total of 20 to 25 percentage points, said Hill. “You have to go back to the [savings and loan] crisis and the global financial crisis to see such big declines in property valuations,” he said.</p><p> The volume of distressed commercial real estate grew by $8 billion in the second quarter, reflecting the rise in cases where the owners defaulted or lenders foreclosed, according to data provider MSCI Real Assets. That is the biggest quarterly increase since the second quarter of 2020.</p><p> While most of the new funds are looking to buy property, some are planning to lend to property owners and fill the void left by the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-lending-by-mortgage-reits-has-dried-up-49551878?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">cutback in activity</a> from regional banks and mortgage real-estate investment trusts. With less competition, the lenders who are still active are able to charge higher rates and get better deal terms from borrowers.</p><p> Invesco Real Estate, which has a long track record of raising funds from institutional investors for real-estate credit funds, is raising its first such fund targeting the retail audience.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Is commercial real estate undervalued right now? Why or why not?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Many of the new funds, such as those being raised by Invesco and Cohen &amp; Steers, are targeting individual investors. Smaller investors have shown an enormous appetite for property investments in recent years, especially with the growth of the nontraded real-estate investment trust industry which raised about $100 billion in the past seven years.</p><p> But many of the nontraded REITs that were formed before last year&#39;s rise in interest rates have been under pressure to redeem money back to investors who want to cash out. Over $9 billion was redeemed in the first six months of this year, according to Stanger, and many investors have been forced to wait to get their money because of the rush to the redemption door.</p><p> Still, the new funds will be facing a lot of competition from cash-rich funds aimed at institutions. Opportunistic real-estate funds run by private-equity firms have nearly $145 billion in so-called dry powder for future investments, up from $120 billion at the end of last year, according to data firm Preqin.</p><p> It is still possible that distressed opportunities won&#39;t arise if the US economy has <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/what-top-executives-are-saying-about-a-soft-landing-4daf9123?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a soft landing</a> , in which inflation is tamed by the Federal Reserve without tipping the economy into recession.</p><p> Sales volume will likely increase when debt markets stabilize and values become more clear. “Broadly speaking, people are waiting to see what the world looks like,” said Michael Stark, co-head of the PJT Park Hill Real Estate Group, a global advisory firm and placement agent. “They&#39;re waiting for motivated sellers.”</p><p> Write to Peter Grant at <a href="mailto:peter.grant@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">peter.grant@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 15 Aug 2023 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/wall-street-is-ready-to-scoop-up-commercial-real-estateon-the-cheap-6edac64f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/wall-street-is-ready-to-scoop-up-commercial-real-estateon-the-cheap-6edac64f<author><![CDATA[Peter Grant]]></author><category>商业地产</category><category>Marine Transport</category><category>信托/基金/金融工具</category><category>投资信托</category><category>房地产投资信托</category><category>Real Estate Services/Transactions</category><category> Freight Transport/Logistics</category><category> Commercial/Industrial Real Estate</category><category>房地产/建筑</category><category>金融服务</category><category>投资/证券</category><category>Marine Freight</category><category>房地产</category><category>Water Transport/Shipping</category><category> Transportation/Logistics</category><category> Ownership Changes</category><category> Physical Asset Transactions</category><category>企业行动</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>商业房地产</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Cohen &amp; Steers</category><category> CNS</category><category> Goldman Sachs</category><category> GS</category><category> EQT Exeter</category><category> ownership changes</category><category> physical asset transactions</category><category>企业行动</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>marine transport</category><category>信托</category><category>资金</category><category>金融工具</category><category>投资信托</category><category>房地产投资信托</category><category>real estate services</category><category> transactions</category><category> freight transport</category><category> logistics</category><category> commercial</category><category> industrial real estate</category><category>房地产</category><category>建造</category><category>金融服务</category><category>投资</category><category>证券</category><category>marine freight</category><category> water transport</category><category> shipping</category><category> transportation </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Argentina’s Financial Markets Plummet After Right-Wing Outsider Wins Primary Vote]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>哈维尔·米雷 (Javier Milei) 在 10 月总统选举前的初选中获得大部分选票后，央行贬值比索的官方汇率<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001132905"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="486" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835118?width=860&amp;height=486" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">极右翼总统候选人哈维尔·米雷周日在布宜诺斯艾利斯的竞选总部发表讲话。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：alejandro pagni/法新社/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001132905"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ryan-dube" itemprop="url" rel="author">Ryan Dubé</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/juan-forero" itemprop="url" rel="author">Juan Forero</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated Aug. 14, 2023 2:42 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentinas-dollar-bonds-plummet-after-far-right-outsider-wins-primary-vote-b7ab9b72"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Argentina&#39;s dollar bonds tumbled and the peso weakened on Monday, a day after a libertarian outsider positioned himself as <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentine-presidential-primary-voters-propel-far-right-outsider-to-surprise-win-ec24e5b4?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the country&#39;s leading hopeful</a> ahead of October&#39;s election.</p><p> The tumult came after Javier Milei, a 52-year-old economist who rails against what he calls “the political caste,” took more votes in a Sunday primary than the center-right Together for Change coalition and the ruling Peronist movement&#39;s candidate, Economy Minister Sergio Massa.</p><p> Argentina&#39;s dollar bonds slid about 14% in early trading, though the initial knee-jerk reaction had little volume behind it, according to Lucas Martin, emerging markets sovereign debt strategist at Bank of America. Those losses were cut in half to about 7% on the day as trading progressed.央行将比索的官方汇率贬值，比索贬值超过20%，至1美元兑换350左右。 The peso&#39;s black-market rate also depreciated on the streets of Buenos Aires, trading more than 10% weaker at about 690 per dollar.</p><p>投资者原本预计“共同谋变”联盟会在投票率较低的投票中表现更好。</p><p> “The low turnout and surprise results have contributed to increased political and market uncertainty,” said Jared Lou, portfolio manager at William Blair Investment Management in Chicago. “鉴于经济状况不佳，选民似乎要求变革。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=FDB4DFD7-9FD4-49A6-9874-2C3D318261D2&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fargentinas-dollar-bonds-plummet-after-far-right-outsider-wins-primary-vote-b7ab9b72&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">巴西和阿根廷领导人重新提出了共同货币的想法，以促进贸易并减少该地区对美元的依赖。 WSJ&#39;s Samantha Pearson explains why it is unlikely to be implemented soon.照片：伊芙·哈特利<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>US investors pulled out of Argentina&#39;s stock market, sending the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/ARGT" class="company-name">Global X MSCI Argentina ETF</a> down as much as 6% in early Monday trading, setting the stage for its worst day in more than a year. The fund traded 2.4% lower on the day as of noon in New York.</p><p> In a radio interview on Monday, Milei said his win was an “enormous slap in the face” to the government of President Alberto Fernández, who had a 75% disapproval rating in one poll and whose term ends in December.</p><p> “They don&#39;t have any idea of how to explain what they&#39;re going to do from here to December,” he said of the Fernández government, on Radio Rivadavia.</p><p> A populist upstart who pledges to close the central bank, replace the peso with the dollar and slash spending, Milei took 30% of ballots. In an election that decides who runs in the first-round presidential vote in October, Milei topped Patricia Bullrich, a hard-on-crime conservative from Together for Change and a former security minister who got 28.3%, and Massa, who is considered more centrist and business friendly than the president. Massa took 27.3% of the vote.</p><p> The vote took place in a country suffering its worst economic crisis since its <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB1028667586359671120?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">2001 financial meltdown</a> . About 40% of Argentines now live in poverty. Inflation tops 116%, making it difficult for families to buy enough to eat and for businesses to function.</p><p> Milei has tapped into bubbling anger, assuring Argentines that if they drastically scale back the government by closing ministries the country will regain its foothold.</p><p> “Today, we stood up to say enough with this decadent model,” Milei said late Sunday in front of cheering supporters. “I invite Argentines to participate in the liberal revolution.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835300?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Inflation in Argentina tops 116%, making it difficult for families to buy enough to eat.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Natacha Pisarenko/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Milei&#39;s strong showing sets up a three-way race that pits him against the two traditional political coalitions. Political analysts say Bullrich, the conservative, will likely be his toughest rival in October amid a backlash against the Peronists, whose rule during most of the last 20 years has been marked by <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/outgoing-argentine-president-to-leave-big-tab-for-successor-1449178707?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a sharp rise in public spending</a> amid generous state subsidies and social programs.</p><p> While acknowledging that some Argentines want Milei, Bullrich said she, too, represents change.</p><p> “That&#39;s represented by Milei, but us as well,” said Bullrich publicly, who has pledged to move quickly to cut the fiscal deficit and dismantle currency controls. “It&#39;s really important that in this time, from here to the election, we represent this change with a lot of fervor.”</p><p> Bullrich&#39;s, coalition ruled from 2015 to 2019 under then President Mauricio Macri. He tried to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/gradualism-is-dead-argentina-faces-pressure-to-hasten-economic-overhaul-1527586201?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">gradually reduce the deficit</a> inherited from a previous Peronist government without sparking social upheaval. That strategy failed as the government took on billions of dollars in debt and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentinas-peso-plunges-to-record-low-1535578085?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">inflation surged higher</a> . Many Argentines haven&#39;t forgotten.</p><p></p> Maria Colman Rodríguez, who has three children to feed but no job, said she feels as if “no politician helps us.”<p></p><p> “I&#39;m betrayed by all of them,” she said. “They all promise things and do not deliver.”</p><p> “Milei could be a hope for us,” she added. “We have to believe in someone who is different.”</p><p> The candidate offers up some of the prescriptions economists say Argentina badly needs, such as opening the country to trade, reducing taxes and privatizing state-owned companies to curb spending. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835299?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Argentina is suffering its worst economic crisis in more than 20 years.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: luis robayo/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> He also has a radically different social vision: He has pledged to end public schools, supports a market for people to sell their organs, proposes to expand access to guns and to end legal abortion.</p><p> Milei acknowledged that his sharp attacks on the political establishment put off some Argentines.</p><p> “I say what I think,” he said last year. “I act and work along my liberal principles, no matter who likes it or not.”</p><p> But Milei as president would likely have little support in the opposition-controlled congress, which he has regularly lambasted, making it difficult to pass his ambitious changes. And austerity measures would also likely face stiff opposition from powerful unions and social movements.</p><p> In a research note on Monday, analysts at Citi Research said Milei&#39;s proposal to dollarize the economy was a concern for investors because of the challenges of implementation.</p><p> “Argentina has no liquid reserves and would struggle to obtain funding in the form of debt or investment,” the note said. “Additionally, a proposal this disruptive would likely face resistance in government.”</p><p> For now, Argentines face more hardship. Monday&#39;s weakening of the peso will likely send inflation even higher, economists say.</p><p> “If this 20% depreciation of the peso sticks, we are going to see a lot of inflation in the coming days,” said Felipe Camargo, an economist who covers Latin America at Oxford Economics, a consulting firm.</p><p> Fausto Spotorno, an economist, said he and his wife had been in the process of buying a new car, but when they went to the vendor on Monday to sign papers, they were told that sales were put on hold indefinitely amid the market uncertainty.</p><p> “Companies, factories just don&#39;t know what to do with the stocks they&#39;re holding,” said Spotorno. “We&#39;re in that place where you don&#39;t know whether or not, economically, things will be fixed in the next 10 months.”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Kejal Vyas, Eric Wallerstein, and Silvina Frydlewsky contributed to this article.</p><p>写信给 Ryan Dubé： <a href="mailto:ryan.dube@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">ryan.dube@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 18:42:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentinas-dollar-bonds-plummet-after-far-right-outsider-wins-primary-vote-b7ab9b72</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentinas-dollar-bonds-plummet-after-far-right-outsider-wins-primary-vote-b7ab9b72<author><![CDATA[Ryan DubéJuan Forero]]></author><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家/总统选举</category><category>货币/货币市场</category><category>外汇市场</category><category>Commodity/Financial Market News</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>总统选举</category><category>钱</category><category>货币市场</category><category>外汇市场</category><category>商品</category><category>financial market news</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</c